# 1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)

# 🔹 Meaning of Citizenship

Citizenship means:

👉 Legal membership of a country.

Citizens enjoy:

* Political rights
* Civil rights
* Constitutional protections

Examples:

* Right to vote
* Right to contest elections

---

# 🔵 Constitutional Provisions

Citizenship provisions are in:

### Part II (Articles 5–11)

📌 Constitution does NOT permanently define citizenship law.

Parliament has power to regulate citizenship.

---

# 🔹 Citizenship Act, 1955

Main law dealing with citizenship in India.

---

# 🔴 Ways to Acquire Citizenship

## 1️⃣ By Birth

Born in India under certain conditions.

---

## 2️⃣ By Descent

Citizenship through parents.

---

## 3️⃣ By Registration

Given to persons of Indian origin under conditions.

---

## 4️⃣ By Naturalization

Foreigner becomes citizen after fulfilling conditions.

---

## 5️⃣ By Incorporation of Territory

If new territory joins India.

Example:

* Pondicherry
* Sikkim

---

# 🔹 Loss of Citizenship

Citizenship can be lost by:

## 1️⃣ Renunciation

Voluntarily giving up citizenship.

---

## 2️⃣ Termination

Automatically ends after acquiring foreign citizenship.

---

## 3️⃣ Deprivation

Government removes citizenship in certain cases.

---

# 🔵 Single Citizenship

India follows:
👉 Single Citizenship

Unlike USA:

* No separate state citizenship.

📌 Promotes national unity.

---

# 🔴 Overseas Citizenship of India (OCI)

OCI provides:

* Limited lifelong visa benefits
* Economic & educational facilities

📌 OCI is NOT dual citizenship.

Very important UPSC point.

---

# 🔹 National Register of Citizens (NRC)

Purpose:
👉 Identify genuine Indian citizens.

Frequently linked with:

* Citizenship issues
* Migration debates

---

# 🔹 Citizenship Amendment Act (CAA), 2019

Provides fast-track citizenship to certain persecuted minorities from:

* Pakistan
* Bangladesh
* Afghanistan

📌 Frequently asked in current affairs context.

